Ce que je dis à mes amis non-américains
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad and my foreign friends always ask me with various degrees of perplexity: but what is happening in your country ?
Here's what I tell them.
Firstly, be careful not to misinterpret the 2016 elections.
Unlike certain comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elites.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet Trump missed winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand votes had been expressed differently in these states, Trump would have lost the electoral college and the presidency.
It is said that Trump's victory raises the true problem of the rise in social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest best-seller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the huge difference between California and the Appalachians.
The research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income whites without university degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically sat at the bottom of the inequality scale.
In 1999, the mortality rates among those without higher education were around 30% lower than those of African Americans; in 2015, they were 30% higher.
Moreover, employment in the industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for working-class whites, has strongly decreased over the past generation, to only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were won over by Trump's promises to shake things up and bring jobs back to the industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation are likely to make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is not to underestimate Trump's communications skills.
Many people are shocked by his Twitter rants and his scandalous disdain for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize viewers' attention, and the best way to achieve that is to make extreme statements, without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his permanent campaign centered on himself to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote moves towards the political center in order to attract more support.
It's what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, claims he won the popular vote and acts as if this were really the case, which pleases his core voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist nominations to the Department of Defense, the State and National Security Department, his choice for the Environmental Protection Agency and for the Ministry of Health and Human Services are at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His staff at the White House is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he wants to satisfy both camps at the same time.
Fourthly, one should not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite its many problems, is not the Italy of 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure that the government is harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of power balance that makes it difficult to exercise this power.
A joke about this topic says that the founders created a political system such that it is impossible for King George to rule over us - impossible for him or for anyone.
Inefficiency has been put to the service of freedom.
The Trump presidency is still at its beginning and we cannot be certain of what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
Up to now, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have watched over this balance of power within the administration, according to Madison's wishes.
And the permanent officials of executive services still weigh in with their weight.
Finally, my friends are wondering what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I worry less about China's rise in power than Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about freeloaders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems of the international order under US leadership, the world is thriving, and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can claim with certainty that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan and other countries to manage international issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's and his members' statements suggest that he may continue to do so.
After all, the power to constrain and the power to persuade of the United States, in large part, come from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has few).
However, the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
The Trump budget director talks about a power budget, with budget cuts made on the Department of State and the United Nations system.
Other government members plead to replace multilateral trade agreements with bilateral "fair and balanced" arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to face climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to reassure them on these issues.
But I cannot.
